    section(class="binge-annotation", id="intro-animations")
      p In college, I was introduced to motion graphics. Though there were already well-established masters of the medium &mdash; pioneers like <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saul_Bass">Saul Bass</a> and contemporary studios like <a href="www.troika.tv">Troika</a> stand out as memorable &mdash; me and my classmates felt like we were on the cutting edge of it all. To us, the pinnacle of motion graphics was the <a href="http://www.artofthetitle.com/">intro animation</a>. We had <a href="http://vimeo.com/384423">entire assignments</a> devoted to them. 
      p But on the internet the intro animation soon became a joke, put to laughable use by restaurants and bars trying to recreate the spirit of their brick-and-mortar establishment online. From a pinnacle to the nadir: the &ldquo;skip intro&rdquo; button, a patch in the design whose existance acknowledges that the decision to hide important content behind a song-and-dance was a bad one.

    section(class="binge-annotation", id="simulations")
      p I initially just wanted this link to be about <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/23/business/23checkout.html?_r=0">the effectiveness of different forms of checkout systems</a>. In <a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=grocery+store+checkout+line+analysis">trying to find something good</a>, I came across <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d6pdZJ5qq-0">this video simulating a bizarrely-laid-out grocery store</a>, which ultimately led me to the website of <a href="http://www.simio.com/index.html">Simio</a>, the company behind the <a href="http://www.simio.com/products/">$4,850</a> software package used to produce that video. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simulation">Simulation</a>, naturally, is an established industry with an <a href="http://wintersim.org/">annual conference</a>. Here is a paper from the 1969 conference titled <a href="http://informs-sim.org/wsc69papers/1969_0021.pdf">Simulation Models for Evaluation of Airport Baggage-Handling Systems</a>.